   Date: 19 Oct 89 01:00:58 GMT
   From: cjsv@cs.adfa.oz.au (Christopher J S Vance)

   My guess is that every root server is expected to load all domains
   immediately below the root (including se) and therefore they already
   know what these domains are without requiring the root domain itself to
   have NS records pointing down to them. 

Sorry, but that turns out not to be the case.  It happens that the
machines that act as name servers for the root zone are also name
servers for a number of other zones, but there is no requirement that
they serve any particular top-level zone; it's strictly an
administrative decision, presumably based on whether or not the
administrators responsible for the root zone (the NIC staff) are
responsible for the top-level zone in question.  The .US zone, for
example, is and always has been served by a separate set of machines.

--Rob Austein, MIT

